I think the best way to go about this is to have:
```python
def ipv4(self, network=False, address_class=None, private=None):
    if address_class is not None or private is not None:
        if private is True:
            return self.ipv4_private(address_class=address_class, network=network)
        else:
            return self.ipv4_public(address_class=address_class, network=network)
    # old logic here...
```

output from this simple program:
```c++
#include <iostream>

using namespace std;

int main() {
  cout << static_cast<float>(1/2) << endl;
  cout << static_cast<float>(1) / static_cast<float>(2) << endl;
  cout << static_cast<float>(3/2) << endl;
  cout << static_cast<float>(3) / static_cast<float>(2) << endl;
  return 0;
}
```
is
```
0
0.5
0
0.5
1
1.5
```
So you do need it

I think it is normal these days to use braces for if..else even if there is only one statement. i.e.:

```js
if (foo) {
  ...
} else {
  ...
}
```

Again, there is probably an eslint rule for this somewhere.

@goosalex I think it would be cleaner to use reflection at this stage to call corresponding methods then specifying some list of dependencies (this might change without failing), also this does not mimic the exact Spark behaviour.

What I think would be the best to try calling `getLocalUserJarsForShell(conf)` if the method exists we can call it and can continue, if it doesn't we can fallback to Utils.getUserJars. This way, the internal implementation of these methods remains hidden, but we can work on both Spark 2.1.1 and 2.1.0 at the same time.

